Similarity manipulation

A minimal group paradigm was used to manipulate the similarity between the participant and four targets based on an arbitrary characteristic (i.e. a bogus cognitive style). The participant was assigned to one of two cognitive styles (Overestimator, Underestimator), allegedly based on their performance on a dot estimation task. In reality, the assignment was preset and counterbalanced across participants. Next, participants completed an associative learning task to learn the cognitive styles of the four targets.

Learning of cognitve styles

Participants completed a minimum of 10 blocks of trials of the learning task. Within each block, participants had to categorize as Overestimator or Underestimator each of the 4 targets once, plus their own cognitive style (“You” trials). Participants completed additional blocks of trials until each stimulus was categorized correctly in at least 8 of the last 10 blocks completed, or after they reached 30 blocks.

Number of learning blocks

# compute number of blocks and accuracy in the last 10 trials 
d.learn %>%
  dplyr::group_by(id) %>%
  dplyr::filter(block>(max(block)-10)) %>%
  dplyr::summarise('N blocks'=max(block), 'Accuracy'=mean(accuracy)) %>%
  get_summary_stats('N blocks', 'Accuracy', type='common', 
                    show=c('n', 'mean', 'sd', 'median', 'min', 'max')) %>%
  kbl(digits=2) %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options=c('hover', 'condensed'), full_width=F, position='center')
variable n mean sd median min max
Accuracy 64 0.93 0.04 0.94 0.76 1
N blocks 64 12.42 4.59 10.00 10.00 31

*Note that due to a coding error, two participants completed 31 blocks instead of the maximum of 30.


Data exclusion

Data of 2 participants who did not achieve an accuracy of at least 80% for each of the stimuli in the last 10 learning blocks were excluded from the statistical analyses following the preregistered criterion.

d.learn.excl <- d.learn %>%
  
  # compute accuracy in the last 10 trials for each stimulus
  dplyr::group_by(id, similarity, identity) %>%
  dplyr::filter(block>(max(block)-10)) %>%
  dplyr::summarise(acc=mean(accuracy), n_blocks=max(block)) %>%

  # identify participants who did not learn all stimuli 
  #   with at least 80% accuracy
  filter(acc<0.8 | n_blocks>29)

# mark participants to excluded from both CET and EET analyses
excl.id <- as.character(unique(d.learn.excl$id))
d.quest <- d.quest %>%
  mutate(exclude=id %in% excl.id) %>%
  mutate(exclude=factor(exclude, levels=c(TRUE, FALSE), 
                        labels=c('Excluded ID', 'Analysis sample')))

# demographics of analysis sample

Face ratings

Before and after learning the cognitive styles, participants judged how similar they felt to each of the 4 targets (similarity), how much they liked them (likability), and how sympathetic they found them (sympathy). Ratings were performed on a 9-point scale.

# Similarity
# ~~~~~~~~~~
# means & confidence intervals (within-subject, method from Morey 2008)
descr.similarity <- summarySEwithin(data=d.ratings, measurevar='rating_similarity', 
                                    betweenvars=NULL, withinvars=c('time', 'similarity'), 
                                    idvar='id', na.rm=FALSE, conf.interval=0.95)

# figure

Similarity

To check whether participants perceived as more similar the targets with whom they shared the same cognitive style, compared to those paired with the opposite cognitive style, a repeated-measures ANOVA was conducted with Similarity (similar target, dissimilar target) and Time (pre-learning, post-learning) as within-subject factors.

# anova
m.similarity <- aov_4(rating_similarity ~ time*similarity + (time*similarity|id), d.ratings)
kbl(nice(m.similarity, es='pes'), caption='ANOVA (Similarity ratings)') %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options=c('hover', 'condensed'), full_width=F, position='center')
ANOVA (Similarity ratings)
Effect df MSE F pes p.value
time 1, 61 0.80 15.75 *** .205 <.001
similarity 1, 61 1.70 13.34 *** .179 <.001
time:similarity 1, 61 1.53 15.60 *** .204 <.001

Post-hoc tests were applied to follow up the significant Similarity * Time. P-values are adjusted for multiple testing using the Holm-Bonferroni method.

# Follow-up pairwise comparisons 

# pairwise comparisons by Time  
# ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
ph.similarity.bytime <- d.ratings %>%
  group_by(time) %>%
  pairwise_t_test(rating_similarity~similarity, paired=TRUE, detailed=TRUE)

# add effect size
ph.similarity.bytime <-d.ratings %>%
  group_by(time) %>%
  cohens_d(rating_similarity~similarity, paired=TRUE) %>%
  inner_join(ph.similarity.bytime) %>%
  select('Condition 1'=group1, 'Condition 2'=group2, 'N'=n1, 
         'Estimate'=estimate, 't'=statistic, 'DF'=df, 'p'=p, 
         'CI Low'=conf.low, 'CI High'=conf.high, "Cohen's d"=effsize)

# pairwise comparisons by Similarity  
# ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
# t-tests
ph.similarity.bytarget <- d.ratings %>%
  dplyr::group_by(similarity) %>%
  pairwise_t_test(rating_similarity~time, paired=TRUE, detailed=TRUE) 

# add effect size
ph.similarity.bytarget <-d.ratings %>%
  dplyr::group_by(similarity) %>%
  cohens_d(rating_similarity~time, paired=TRUE) %>%
  inner_join(ph.similarity.bytarget) %>%
  select('Condition 1'=group1, 'Condition 2'=group2, 'N'=n1, 
         'Estimate'=estimate, 't'=statistic, 'DF'=df, 'p'=p, 
         'CI Low'=conf.low, 'CI High'=conf.high, "Cohen's d"=effsize)

# merge both groups of comparisons and correct p-value for multiple comparisons
ph.similarity <- rbind(ph.similarity.bytime, ph.similarity.bytarget)
ph.similarity$p <- p.adjust(ph.similarity$p, method='holm')
kbl(ph.similarity, digits=2, caption='Pairwise comparisons (Similarity ratings)') %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options=c('hover', 'condensed'), full_width=F, position='center')

Affective self-projection

Affective state manipulation

At the beginning of each block of the affective self-projection paradigm, participants watched a happy or a sad video aimed to induce positive or negative affective states to the participant. To assess the success of this manipulation, participants were asked to rate their mood on a 11-point slider (1 = negative affect; 11 = positive affect) right after they watched each video (i.e. before the emotion judgment task). Participants also reported their current mood at the end of each block (i.e. after emotion judgment task) to check whether the induced mood was maintained throughout the emotion judgment trials.

# means & confidence intervals (within-subject, method from Morey 2008)
descr.mood <- summarySEwithin(data=d.mood, measurevar='mood', 
                                    betweenvars=NULL, withinvars=c('affect', 'time'), 
                                    idvar='id', na.rm=FALSE, conf.interval=0.95)

# figure
fig.mood <- ggplot(descr.mood, aes(y=mood, x=time, color=affect)) + 
  
  # horizontal line
  geom_hline(yintercept=6, color='grey', size=line_size*0.25) +

  # plot means and CI 
  geom_point(size=point_size) +
  geom_line(aes(group=affect)) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=mood-ci, ymax=mood+ci), width=error_width, size=error_size) + 

  # plot individual observations 
  geom_dotplot(data=d.mood, aes(y=mood, x=time, fill=affect),
               binaxis='y', stackdir='centerwhole', alpha=.3, stroke=0, binwidth=0.25) +
  
  # format
  scale_y_continuous(name='Mood ratings', breaks=seq(1, 11, by=1), limits=c(0, 12)) +
  scale_x_discrete(name='Time', labels=c(pre='Before emotion \njudgement task', post='After emotion \njudgement task')) +
  scale_color_manual(values=color_affect, labels=labels_affect) +
  scale_fill_manual(values=color_affect, labels=labels_affect) +
  my_theme +
  theme(
    axis.title.x=element_blank(),
    )

ANOVA

To assess the success of the affective state manipulations, a repeated-measures ANOVA was conducted on the mood ratings, with Affect induction (positive, negative) and Time of assessment (before, after emotion judgments) as within-subject factors.

m.mood <- aov_4(mood ~ time*affect + (time*affect|id), d.mood)
kable(nice(m.mood, es='pes'), caption='ANOVA (Mood ratings)') %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options=c('hover', 'condensed'), full_width=F, position='center')

affect 1, 61 5.42 320.00 *** .840 <.001

Post-hoc tests were applied to follow-up the significant Affect induction * Time. P-values are adjusted for multiple testing using the Holm-Bonferroni method.

Data exclusion

According to the preregistered criteria, participants who did not feel more positively after watching the happy video compared to the sad video would be excluded from the PSE analysis. As all participants had the expected pattern of mood ratings, none of the participants had to be excluded due to this criterion.

# check if any participant did not report the expected pattern of affect 
# (i.e more positive mood after positive induction than after negative), 
# for both at the beginning of the block, and at the end
# Only exclude if the pattern of affect is not as expected at pre.
d.moodcheck <- d.mood %>%
  select(id, time, affect, mood) %>%
  spread(affect, mood) %>%
  dplyr::group_by(time) %>%
  mutate(`Positive > Negative`=positive>negative) %>%
  ungroup()
  
table1(~`Positive > Negative`|time, d.moodcheck, overall=FALSE)

Yes 62 (100%) 60 (96.8%)
No 0 (0%) 2 (3.2%)

Egocentric biases & Similarity

After each affect induction, participants made emotion judgments about ambiguous facial expressions (happy-sad morphs) of a similar and a dissimilar target. The point of subjective equivalence (PSE) was measured as an indication of the participant’s tendency to judge the expressions as happy. In the current experiment, lower PSEs were indicative of a higher tendency to evaluate the faces as happy (vs. sad).

# means & confidence intervals (within-subject, method from Morey 2008)
descr.pse <- summarySEwithin(data=d.pse, measurevar='pse',
                                    betweenvars=NULL, withinvars=c('affect', 'similarity'),
                                    idvar='id', na.rm=FALSE, conf.interval=0.95)

# figure
fig.pse <- ggplot(descr.pse, aes(y=pse, x=affect, color=similarity, fill=similarity)) +

ANOVA

To check whether the degree of egocentric biases in emotion judgments was modulated by the similarity with the target, a repeated-measures ANOVA was conducted on the PSEs, with Affective State (positive affect, negative affect) and Similarity (similar target, dissimilar target) as within-subject factors.

# anova
m.pse <- aov_4(pse ~ affect*similarity + (affect*similarity|id), d.pse)
kbl(nice(m.pse, es='pes'), caption='ANOVA') %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options=c('hover', 'condensed'), full_width=F, position='center')

Main contrast of interest

The preregistered interaction contrast aimed to directly compare the bias scores for similar vs. dissimilar targets. Individual bias scores were computed as the difference between the PSE estimated for each target in the negative affect condition compared to the positive affect condition. Positive bias scores are indicative of egocentricity, as they reflect a lower tendency to judge the facial expressions as happy after negative affect induction than after positive affect induction.

# compute EEB scores by subtracting PSE_negative minus PSE_positive
d.eeb <- d.pse %>%
  select(id, affect, similarity, pse) %>%
  spread(affect, pse) %>%
  dplyr::group_by(id, similarity) %>%
  mutate(eeb=(negative-positive))
d.eeb <- as.data.frame(d.eeb)
# means & confidence intervals (within-subject, method from Morey 2008)
descr.eeb <- summarySEwithin(data=d.eeb, measurevar='eeb',
                                    betweenvars=NULL, withinvars=c('similarity'),
                                    idvar='id', na.rm=FALSE, conf.interval=0.95)

Equivalence testing

Because null-hypothesis significance testing can only reject the presence of an effect, we cannot conclude that similarity does not influence the degree of egocentric biases based on the non-significant interaction. To test whether egocentric biases were statistically equivalent for similar and dissimilar targets, we applied equivalence testing on the critical interaction contrast using the Two One-Sided Tests procedure (Lakens, 2017). Equivalence bounds were determined based on the preregistered smallest effect size of interest used to decide the study sample size (Cohen’s d = 0.35).

# Two one-sided tests (TOST) procedure for equivalence testing
d.eeb.similar <- d.eeb$eeb[d.eeb$similarity=='similar']
d.eeb.dissimilar <- d.eeb$eeb[d.eeb$similarity=='dissimilar']
sesoi <- 0.35

TOSTER::TOSTpaired(n=length(d.eeb.similar),
                   m1=mean(d.eeb.similar), m2=mean(d.eeb.dissimilar),
                   sd1=sd(d.eeb.similar), sd2=sd(d.eeb.dissimilar),
                   r12=cor(d.eeb.similar, d.eeb.dissimilar),
                   low_eqbound_dz=-sesoi, high_eqbound_dz=sesoi,
                   alpha=0.05, plot=TRUE, verbose=TRUE)

Cognitive self-projection

A linear mixed-effect model (LMM) was used to examine the influence of perceived similarity on self-projection. Specifically, we tested whether the own attitudes with respect to a series of statements (Self-ratings) predicted the inferred attitudes of others (Other-ratings), and whether this relationship was dependent on the similarity with the target (Similarity).

The LMM used to test our hypothesis was as follows:

Other-rating ~ Self-rating + Similarity + Self-rating * Similarity + (1 + Self-rating | Participant) + (1 + Similarity | Item) + (1 | Target identity)

Model specification

Fixed effects

The Other-ratings were used as the dependent variable in the LMM. The Self-ratings, Similarity and the interaction Self-ratings*Similarity were included as fixed effects. Effect coding was set for the categorical predictor (Similar vs. Dissimilar), and self-ratings were mean-centered.

  • A significant main effect of Self-ratings would indicate that individuals use the own attitudes to predict the attitudes of other people (self-projection).

  • A significant interaction Self-rating*Similarity would provide evidence that the degree of self-projection during social inferences depends on the perceived similarity with the target.

Random effects

The LMM included random intercepts for participants (1|Participant), items (1|Item) and target (1|Target identity). To determine the random slopes, iterative rounds of principal component analysis (PCA) were conducted to remove the random slopes from the maximal model that explained zero variance or which led to convergence issues. We followed the following steps:

  1. Perform a PCA on the maximal LMM supported by the data and task design. If all principle components (PC) explain non-zero variance, use the maximal LMM as the final model. If the maximal model does not converge, proceed to step 2.

  2. If one (or more) PC explain zero variance, fit the LMM without the correlation parameters. If this model converges, take this as the final model. If not, proceed to step 3.

  3. Remove the predictor with the smallest variance of random slopes, and add the correlation parameters to this reduced model. Perform a PCA to check whether all PCs explain non-zero variance. If not, repeat steps 2 and 3 until finding the parsimonious LMM that converges.


M1.1: maximal

We started with the maximal LMM allowed by the data and task design:

Other-rating ~ Self-rating + Similarity + Self-rating * Similarity + (1 + Self-rating * Similarity | Participant) + (1 + Self-rating * Similarity | Item) + (1 + Similarity | Target identity)

The maximal LMM led to singular fit. In addition, several PCs explained 0 variance, which suggests that the random-effect structure was not optimal. We therefore looked for a more parsimonious version of the LMM (see M1.2).

# NOTE: this is actually not the model that was included in the preregistration as the "maximal model". The preregistered model [Other-rating ~ Self*Similarity + (Self*Similarity|ID) + (Similarity|Item) + (Similarity|Target)] was actually not maximal and as it didn't include the by-item random slope for rating_self and the interaction self*similarity.

# M1.1: maximal model allowed by the data and task design
m11 <- lmer(rating_other ~ rating_self_cen*similarity + (1+rating_self_cen*similarity|id) + (1+rating_self_cen*similarity|item) + (1+similarity|identity), data=d.cet)

M1.2: maximal’

This LMM was composed by the same random effects as the maximal model (M1.1), but without the correlation parameters:

Other-rating ~ Self-rating + Similarity + Self-rating * Similarity + (1 + Self-rating * Similarity || Participant) + (1 + Self-rating * Similarity || Item) + (1 + Similarity || Target identity)

As this LMM did not converge and several PCs explained 0 variance, we proceeded by reducing the random effects structure (see M2.1).

# M1.2: "maximal" model without correlation parameters
m12 <- lmer(rating_other ~ rating_self_cen*similarity + (1+rating_self_cen*similarity||id) + (1+rating_self_cen*similarity||item) + (1+similarity||identity), data=d.cet)

M2.1: reduced

We first reduced the random effect structure of the maximal model by removing the higher-order random slopes (i.e. interactions), as well as the by-identity random slope of similarity, which explained little variance:

Other-rating ~ Self-rating + Similarity + Self-rating * Similarity + (1 + Self-rating + Similarity | Participant) + (1 + Self-rating + Similarity | Item) + (1 | Target identity)

As before, the last PCs of the by-id and by-participant random effects explained less than 1% of the variance, and the model lead to singular fits. We continued by assessing the same model, but removing the correlation parameters (see M2.2).

# M2.1: model without (rating_self_cen:similarity|identity), (rating_self_cen:similarity|identity), (similarity|identity)
m21 <- lmer(rating_other ~ rating_self_cen*similarity + (1+rating_self_cen+similarity|id) + (1+rating_self_cen+similarity|item) + (1|identity), data=d.cet)

M2.2: reduced’

The model M2.2 without the correlation parameters was as follows:

Other-rating ~ Self-rating + Similarity + Self-rating * Similarity + (1 + Self-rating + Similarity || Participant) + (1 + Self-rating + Similarity || Item) + (1 || Target identity)

This LMM did not converge either. Several PCs, as well as the by-id and by-participant random effects explained near-to-zero variance. Therefore, we reduced the random effects structure once more by removing the random slopes with smallest variance in M3.

# M2.2: model without (rating_self_cen:similarity|identity), (rating_self_cen:similarity|identity), (similarity|identity), and without correlation parameters
m22 <- lmer(rating_other ~ rating_self_cen*similarity + (1+rating_self_cen+similarity||id) + (1+rating_self_cen+similarity||item) + (1|identity), data=d.cet)

M3: final

We removed the random slopes with smallest variance from the last model tested ( Similarity | Participant, Self-rating | Item). The resulting LMM was as follows:

Other-rating ~ Self-rating + Similarity + Self-rating * Similarity + (1 + Self-rating | Participant) + (1 + Similarity | Item) + (1 | Target identity)

This time the model converged and all PCs explained non-zero variance (Yay!). We used this model to test the hypothesis.

# M3: model without (similarity|id), (rating_self_cen|id)
m31 <- lmer(rating_other ~ rating_self_cen*similarity + (1+rating_self_cen|id) + (1+similarity|item) + (1|identity), data=d.cet)

Model comparison

As one last step before deciding for the final model, we compared the maximal model (M1.1), as well as the reduced models (M2.1, M3), to a null model with no random slopes. Based on the AIC and BIC, all models performed better than the null. M1.1 and M2.2 had better fit than M3, but we decided for the latter because the previous models showed convergence issues and included random factors that explained zero variance.

# null model
m01 <- lmer(rating_other ~ rating_self_cen*similarity + (1|id) + (1|item) + (1|identity), data=d.cet)

# NOTE: use "refit=FALSE" when comparing models that only differ in the random structure, as it is better to compare models with REML. If anova() is performed to compare differences between models differing in fixed effects, then better refit the models with ML.
anova(m01, m11, m21, m31, refit=FALSE)

# run final model
m.cet <- lmer(rating_other ~ rating_self_cen*similarity + (1+rating_self_cen|id) + (1+similarity|item) + (1|identity), data=d.cet)
